The peak season for pneumococcal pneumonia in developed countries is winter66, 86 (Fig. 31-9
), closely corresponding to peak isolation rates of RSV and influenza. In tropical countries, studies have reported either little seasonal variation84 or small peaks in the hot season and the monsoon season83 (Fig. 31-10
). The peaks observed could be explained either by secondary infection on the heels of seasonal viral infections or (in parallel to virus infections) by increased interpersonal transmission of bacteria during seasons when people spend more time indoors.
